          <avActivityHighlights>Wind slabs in the high Alpine regions. Wet and gliding snow at low altitude.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>As a consequence of a moderate wind from northwesterly directions, wind slabs will form at elevated altitudes. &lt;br/&gt; Wind slabs can be released, even by a single winter sport participant. This applies in particular on steep shady slopes in high Alpine regions, as well as on wind-loaded slopes, in the regions exposed to a lot of wind, also at transitions into gullies and bowls. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In isolated cases avalanches can also be triggered in the old snowpack and reach large size. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; On steep slopes and at low altitude more moist avalanches are possible by midday, but they can reach medium size in some cases.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>In the last few days hard wind slabs formed over a wide area. The sometimes storm force wind has transported the new snow significantly. In the vicinity of peaks snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; As a consequence of a moderate wind from northwesterly directions, mostly small wind slabs will form. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Weak layers exist in the old snowpack in particular on steep northwest, north and northeast facing slopes. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Sunshine and high temperatures gave rise to moistening of the old snowpack at low altitude.</snowpackStructureComment>
